@@eThe Great Northern Forest -- Sand-Sea Carters' Guild Routing Brief@@N

The @@ySand-Sea Carters' Guild@@N files the Great Northern Forest under
@@yIndirect Provenance, Class Two@@N: goods originating from or transiting
through the forest eventually reach Mafdet's quays, but rarely in the
same hands that carried them under the canopy. By the time northern
timber, resin, medicinal bark, or mire-clan fish oil arrives at our
Ledger Houses, it has changed ownership two or three times along the
oasis corridors.

That distance does not make the forest irrelevant. It makes it
@@rdifficult to attest@@N.

The @@yLantern Road@@N interests our Harbor Wardens because it functions
as an inland signal system -- lamp-posts at each ford and turn,
maintained by @@gRoadwardens@@N under joint compact. We recognize that
architecture. Our own signal towers along the Tidemouth approach serve
the same purpose: visible proof that someone is maintaining the route.
When Lantern Road lamps go dark, goods stop moving. When goods stop
moving, the oasis corridor contracts. When the corridor contracts,
our manifests thin.

The @@yPassage Tithe@@N -- payment in grain, salt, oil, and iron nails
rather than coin -- is an attestation system whether its architects
knew it or not. Goods paid as tithe carry implicit provenance: the
salt came from somewhere, the oil was rendered by identifiable hands.
Our Ledger Houses could work with that. Coin is anonymous. Commodity
payment is @@gself-documenting@@N.

The @@WNorthern Covenant@@N that governs the road is the kind of
instrument we understand at the Shrine of the First Claw: a sworn
compact between two powers, with penalties for violation. But it
depends on @@yMidgaard@@N and @@yKowloon@@N both honoring their obligations.
Neither city has sworn anything at @@rour@@N shrine. Their compact is
their business -- until it breaks. Then it becomes ours, because
broken compacts produce @@runattested cargo@@N, displaced peoples, and
supply disruption.

The @@rAshfang warbands@@N concern us only as a provenance problem.
Goods seized by raiders and resold carry no legitimate chain of
custody. When forest-origin cargo arrives at our docks with
inconsistent seals, the Quarantine Ledger flags it for secondary
inspection. We do not moralize about banditry. We simply require
documentation. @@dIf you cannot prove where it came from, it does
not leave this port.@@N

The forest feeds us at two removes. We watch it the way a harbor
watches the weather upstream: not because we can control it, but
because @@ywhat happens there arrives here eventually@@N, and we must
be ready to classify it when it does.
